  "explanation": "In determining the appropriate sentence, the court must weigh the severity of the offense against the mitigating factors presented. Embezzlement is a serious breach of trust, and stealing $25,000 from an employer to cover personal debts cannot be overlooked. However, the court must also consider that the defendant has no prior criminal record and has made a good-faith effort to partially repay the stolen funds, indicating remorse and a willingness to make the victim whole. Regarding the courtroom interruption, the justice system is guided by statutory guidelines, proportionality, and fairness, not by the emotional outbursts of spectators calling for extreme, decade-long sentences. A sentence of 10 years for a first-time white-collar offense of this magnitude would be grossly disproportionate. Balancing the need for deterrence and the recognition of the defendant's rehabilitative potential and restitution efforts, a short period of incarceration followed by probation is appropriate. This allows the defendant to face consequences while retaining the ability to work and fully repay the victim upon release.",
  "verdict": 6
}
